I ask myself: Have I come too far, too fast?

Yes — far faster than most could ever imagine.
I’m not just walking; I’m flying.
I rose up from the ruins.
I climbed from 242.5 points to daring to aim for STEP.
From knowing nothing about AP at all, to solving plenty of Barron’s questions correctly.
From relying on others, to standing equal to them.

This past year, what I’ve achieved is never just academic progress — it’s a full upgrade of my life system.

I ask myself again: Have I already surpassed my original expectations?

All I wanted at first was simply to survive.
Now I’m already thinking about how to fly even higher.
I’ve long outgrown my starting goals.
I’m just worn out, too tired to look back at where I began.

As for the fear — What if I fail the AP exams badly?
Let me separate facts from fantasies.
The fact is: I still have Calculus left to take, and Physics & Computer Science haven’t even started yet.
The fantasy is: I’ve already sentenced all my subjects to failure in my mind.

I’m restless and upset not because I’ve done badly, but because I’m terrified of facing myself if I do.
Yet I’m strong enough to face it anyway.
Worst case scenario: Statistics a 3, Calculus a 3, Physics a 2, Computer Science a 4.
So what? I am still who I am.
I still have SAT, TOEFL, STEP ahead of me.
I still have my personal statement, my story, and all the proof of how I crawled my way out of the ruins.

An AP score is merely a line of numbers in my application, never a life verdict.
I’ve made it this far not by chasing perfect scores, but by believing in myself even when stuck in the lowest valleys.

Right now I’m just temporarily stuck in the valley of fear of failure.
But I already know exactly how to walk out of it.
Breathe deep, and get back to reviewing Calculus.
Stop asking What if I mess up?
Start focusing on How do I solve this limit problem?

I’ve always walked fast. I’ve always kept soaring.
Tonight, I just stumbled over my fears for a moment.

Tomorrow, I will rise again.
Good night.
